sec.p:
Thermochemical energy storage (TCES) can convert thermal energy into chemical energy. Gas–solid TCES is often used because the reactants are easy to isolate. A typical TCES process can be described as [21]:1nAB·AB(s)+ΔH⟺nA·As+nB·B(g)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${n}_{AB}\cdot {AB}_{(s)}+\Delta \mathrm{H}\stackrel{ }{\iff } {n}_{A}\cdot {A}_{\left(s\right)}+{n}_{B}\cdot {B}_{(g)}$$\end{document}

The interaction effects between the reaction kinetics and heat transfer are complicated for a TCES process. Therefore, it is important to obtain the clear reaction kinetic parameters. Matsuda [183] studied the decomposition kinetics of Ca(OH)2 from the 1980s and obtained the governing equations. The common format which can be used to describe reaction kinetics of both Ca(OH)2 and Mg(OH)2 are shown as follows [184–186]:2dXdt=k(T)·h(p,peq,T,Teq)·f(X)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{array}{c}\frac{dX}{dt}=k(T)\cdot h(p,{p}_{eq},{T,T}_{eq})\cdot f(X)\end{array}$$\end{document}

